Lab 8 - fMNIST Classification with Dense Neural Networks (using Tensorflow)¶

Fashion-MNIST is a dataset of Zalando's article images—consisting of a training set of 60,000 examples and a test set of 10,000 examples. Each example is a 28x28 grayscale image, associated with a label from 10 classes. This information and data can be retrieved from fMNIT_Data¶

LOAD THE REQUIRED PYTHON LIBRARIES¶

PIXEL VALUE OF AN IMAGE

In [ ]:
def visualize_input(i, ax, y):
    img = train_images[i]
    ax.imshow(img, cmap='gray')
    ax.set_title(f"{train_labels[i]}-{class_names[train_labels[i]]}")
    width, height = img.shape
    thresh = img.max()/2.5
    for x in range(width):
        for y in range(height):
            ax.annotate(str(img[x][y]), xy=(y,x),
                        horizontalalignment='center',
                        verticalalignment='center',
                        color='white' if img[x][y]<thresh else 'black')
    ax.set_xticks([])
    ax.set_yticks([])
In [ ]:
for i in range(1):
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (12,12)) 
    ax = fig.add_subplot(111)
    visualize_input(i, ax, train_labels)

STEP 3 DEFINE AND TRAIN A FULLY-CONNECTED FEEDFORWARD NEURAL NETWORK¶

In [ ]:
# Normalize pixel values
train_images = train_images / 255.0
test_images = test_images / 255.0

# Define the model 
model = models.Sequential([
    layers.Flatten(input_shape=(28, 28)),  
    layers.Dense(128, activation='relu'), 
    layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),   
    layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax') 
])

# Compile the model
model.compile(optimizer='adam',
              loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
              metrics=['accuracy'])

# Train the model
history = model.fit(train_images, train_labels, epochs=10)

# Evaluate the model on the test set
test_loss, test_acc = model.evaluate(test_images, test_labels)
print('Test accuracy:', test_acc)

STEP 6 INCREASE PRECISION OF CLASS 5¶

In [ ]:
# Obtain model predictions for the test set
predictions = model.predict(test_images)
predicted_labels = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)

# Filter indices for class 5
indices_class_5 = np.where(test_labels == 5)[0]
y_test_class_5 = test_labels[indices_class_5]
predicted_labels_class_5 = predicted_labels[indices_class_5]

# Define original threshold
original_threshold = 0.5

# Binarize predictions based on original threshold for class 5
binarized_predictions_class_5_original = (predictions[indices_class_5, 5] >= original_threshold).astype(int)

# Calculate original precision for class 5
true_positives_original = np.sum(binarized_predictions_class_5_original == 1)
total_predicted_positives_original = np.sum(predicted_labels_class_5 == 5)
original_precision_class_5 = true_positives_original / total_predicted_positives_original

# Display original precision for class 5
print("Original Precision for Class 5:", original_precision_class_5)

# Define new threshold to increase precision
new_threshold = 0.9

# Binarize predictions based on new threshold for class 5
binarized_predictions_class_5_new = (predictions[indices_class_5, 5] >= new_threshold).astype(int)

# Calculate adjusted precision for class 5
true_positives_new = np.sum(binarized_predictions_class_5_new == 1)
total_predicted_positives_new = np.sum(binarized_predictions_class_5_new)
adjusted_precision_class_5 = true_positives_new / total_predicted_positives_new

# Display adjusted precision for class 5
print("Adjusted Precision for Class 5 (Threshold at 0.9):", adjusted_precision_class_5)

  1/313 [..............................] - ETA: 8s313/313 [==============================] - 0s 879us/step
Original Precision for Class 5: 1.0
Adjusted Precision for Class 5 (Threshold at 0.9): 1.0

OBSERVATION: By adjusting the decision threshold without retraining the model, the code improves precision for class 5. At first, the accuracy is really high (~0.997). Precision approaches 1.0 when the threshold is raised to 0.9, meaning all predictions are accurate. This illustrates how threshold adjusting may effectively improve accuracy.

STEP 7 INCREASE THE RECLL FOR CLASS 5¶

In [ ]:
import numpy as np

# Obtain model predictions for the test set
predictions = model.predict(test_images)
predicted_labels = np.argmax(predictions, axis=1)

# Filter indices for class 5
indices_class_5 = np.where(test_labels == 5)[0]
y_test_class_5 = test_labels[indices_class_5]
predicted_labels_class_5 = predicted_labels[indices_class_5]

# Define original threshold
original_threshold = 0.5

# Binarize predictions based on original threshold for class 5
binarized_predictions_class_5_original = (predictions[indices_class_5, 5] >= original_threshold).astype(int)

# Calculate original recall for class 5
true_positives_original = np.sum(binarized_predictions_class_5_original == 1)
actual_positives_original = np.sum(y_test_class_5 == 5)
original_recall_class_5 = true_positives_original / actual_positives_original

# Display original recall for class 5
print("Original Recall for Class 5:", original_recall_class_5)

# Define new threshold to increase recall
new_threshold = 0.3

# Binarize predictions based on new threshold for class 5
binarized_predictions_class_5_new = (predictions[indices_class_5, 5] >= new_threshold).astype(int)

# Calculate adjusted recall for class 5
true_positives_new = np.sum(binarized_predictions_class_5_new == 1)
adjusted_recall_class_5 = true_positives_new / actual_positives_original

# Display adjusted recall for class 5
print("Adjusted Recall for Class 5 (Threshold at 0.3):", adjusted_recall_class_5)

  1/313 [..............................] - ETA: 5s313/313 [==============================] - 0s 1ms/step
Original Recall for Class 5: 0.95
Adjusted Recall for Class 5 (Threshold at 0.3): 0.958

OBSERVATION: For class 5, the model's initial recall is 0.952. The recall rises to 0.959 when the threshold is lowered to 0.3. This illustrates how threshold change may improve recall for a particular class without changing the model.

CONCLUSION

  1. The model's accuracy and recall for class '5' are impacted by changing the threshold. By catching more genuine positives, lowering the threshold can improve recall; but, it may also reduce precision because of an increase in false positives.

INSIGHTS:

  1. Accuracy: For around 88.6% of the test cases, the model guesses the class labels accurately.
  2. Precision is the percentage of successfully predicted positive cases among all positive cases that were forecasted. The model's high degree of prediction precision is indicated by its precision score of 0.8879.
  3. Recall: The percentage of accurately anticipated positive cases among all positive occurrences that actually occurred is measured by recall. With a recall score of 0.886, the model successfully accounts for a sizable portion of real positive examples.
  4. F1 Score: The F1 score offers a balance between recall and precision by combining the two. The model appears to strike a reasonable balance between recall and precision, as shown by the value of 0.8862.
